Abstract: Provides relative to bail conditions for defendants alleged to have committed
certain human trafficking offenses.
Present law provides for bail conditions.
Proposed law generally retains present law.
Present law provides bail conditions for defendants who are alleged to have committed
crimes of violence.
Proposed law retains present law.
Proposed law requires the court, as a condition of bail, to impose a restriction that a
defendant who is alleged to have committed the offense of human trafficking or trafficking
of children for sexual purposes refrain from contacting, communicating, or physically
interacting with the victim. Further provides limited exceptions for when the offender is
permitted communication.
Proposed law requires the court, as a condition of bail, to impose a restriction that a
defendant who is alleged to have committed the offense of human trafficking or trafficking
of children for sexual purposes refrain from engaging in work that involves any of the
following:
(1) Working as a driver for a transportation network company.
(2) Operation of any bus, taxicab, or limousine for hire.
(3) Providing in-home services as a service worker entering a residence.
(4) Operation of any carnival or amusement ride.
(5) Acting as a door-to-door solicitor, peddler, or itinerant vendor selling any type of
goods or services including magazines or periodicals or subscriptions to magazines
or periodicals.
(6) Exercising supervisory or disciplinary authority over children.
(7) Operating or participating in the governance of any early learning center, residential
home, or residence in which child care services are provided by a registered family
child care provider or in-home provider.
(Amends C.Cr.P. Art. 320(J)(1); Adds C.Cr.P. Art. 320(J)(4))
